As of https://crrev.com/1204351, absl::optional is now a type alias for

std::optional. We should migrate toward it.



Script:

```

function replace {

echo "Replacing $1 by $2"

git grep -l "$1" \

| cut -f1 -d: \

| grep \

-e "^tools" \

| sort \

| uniq \

| grep \

-e "\.h" \

-e "\.cc" \

-e "\.mm" \

-e "\.py" \

replace "absl::optional" "std::optional"
```

entry.title: [sync] Create/delete account bookmarks upon sign-in/signout
entry.content:
This patch changes sync code to exercise the new BookmarkModel APIs

to create and remove account bookmarks. Namely, this is done from

sync_bookmarks::BookmarkModelView, when the view is about account

bookmarks.



The general idea is that, when sync starts in transport mode for

bookmarks, these folders should be created. Similarly, if sync stops

permanently, these folders and their content should be deleted.



In order to avoid some DCHECK failures until BookmarkModel has

better support for UUIDs, BookmarkModelView is extended with a

workaround to disable some UUID-related DCHECKs for account

bookmarks.



Design doc (sorry, Googlers only):

https://docs.google.com/document/d/1i9XuP0lXOvEbvlwXre-EXMum4dxs_UToCsCcImIPEQU/edit?usp=sharing&resourcekey=0-1t7DIB0kTwaaGMmxtiZLqw

entry.title: Reland "Fix policy component's PRESUBMIT to handle policy removal"
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit ab38f0ad47c2f2b50a848c766970553c4ff44d62



Change from original commit -



Fixed typo and ran `git cl presubmit --force --all`.



Original change's description:

> Fix policy component's PRESUBMIT to handle policy removal

>

> Policy component's PRESUBMIT check makes it impossible to remove support

> for a policy.

>

> From

> https://chromium.googlesource.com/chromium/src/+/main/docs/enterprise/add_new_policy.md#removing-support-for-a-policy

> - removing support for a policy involves updating the policy's YAML

> file and removing its test from policy/test/data/pref_mapping. But a

> PRESUBMIT checks for policy YAML file modifications that do not have an

> equivalent test.

>

> Modify the PRESUBMIT check to skip checking missing tests for

> unsupported policies.

>

> Additionally fix some formatting and grammatical errors.

>

entry.title: Improve AudioRendererMixer sharing across RenderFrames.
entry.content:
It's common for a page to have a lot of YouTube embeds. With the

current code, none of those embeds share a mixer and thus can

trigger the 50 physical stream limit quickly.



AFAICT, there's no good reason to prevent sharing of these streams

across render frames when the default device is used. They are

output only and an uncompromised renderer can't directly observe

any effects (readback for WebAudio and MediaStreams happens

asynchronously below the shared output).



Often the default device is already being shared at the OS level,

so any demultiplexing we do in the renderer seems pointless.



Looking through the history we've always limited the sharing to

per RenderFrameID, but it was only out of an abundance of caution

rather than a particular concern.



For non-default devices there's good reasons we shouldn't share:

permissions are required per-origin to access the non-default

device.

entry.title: Rename {absl => std}::optional in //content/
entry.content:
Automated patch, intended to be effectively a no-op.



Context:

https://groups.google.com/a/chromium.org/g/cxx/c/nBD_1LaanTc/m/ghh-ZZhWAwAJ?utm_medium=email&utm_source=footer



As of https://crrev.com/1204351, absl::optional is now a type alias for

std::optional. We should migrate toward it.



Script:

```

function replace {

echo "Replacing $1 by $2"

git grep -l "$1" \

| cut -f1 -d: \

| grep \

-e "^content" \

| sort \

| uniq \

| grep \

-e "\.h" \

-e "\.cc" \

-e "\.mm" \

-e "\.py" \

| xargs sed -i "s/$1/$2/g"

}

replace "absl::make_optional" "std::make_optional"

replace "absl::optional" "std::optional"

replace "absl::nullopt" "std::nullopt"

replace "absl::in_place" "std::in_place"

replace "absl::in_place_t" "std::in_place_t"

replace "\"third_party\/abseil-cpp\/absl\/types\/optional.h\"" ""

git cl format

```

entry.title: [top chrome] Fix paint invalidation issue during immersive mode
entry.content:
Custom themes with gradients or background images will paint in

such a way that keeps the image position fixed wrt the image

position on the browser window (see

TopContainerBackground::PaintThemeAlignedImage).



In order to retain image position when painting the

TopContainerView as it slides down in immersive mode the view

must be repainted to avoid visual artifacts.



Calling View::SchedulePaint() alone is insufficient as the API

does not correctly repaint child views that host their own layers.



As an immediate fix the TopContainerView also schedules a paint on

child view layers during immersive reveal. Follow up work will

address the root issue in View::SchedulePaint.



Bug: 1502757, 1516979

entry.title: Reland "Enable continuous mode/runtime counter relocation for coverage builds"
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit 0265879ffa10a660230994a3ca36a96c1fec0d18



The original change was reverted because this enabled the continuous

mode on PGO bots, causing them to fail. The continuous mode was enabled

everywhere by the change made in the original CL to test_env.py. It is

believed that the continuous mode is incompatible with pgo builds

because PGO builds make manual calls to compiler-rt to flush the

counters. To address this, this reland wil omit the changes made to

test_env.py. Instead, continuous mode will be enabled on the bots later

by updating the recipe, which is in a separate repository.



Original change's description:

> Enable continuous mode/runtime counter relocation for coverage builds

>

> Enabling the continuous mode for coverage builds allows us to recover

> coverage data for test processes run in sandboxes while avoiding the CQ

> failures that we see with the noncontinuous mode that flushes all the

> counters to disk at process shutdown. This should also be expected to

> recover coverage data for tests that exit abnormally.

>

> Enabling the continuous mode is also the first step in landing several

> changes that will potentially improve instrumented test performance.

>

entry.title: Don't always use current snap ratio to check snappability
entry.content:
This CL fixes the issue that some components use the current snap ratio

to check the snappability even if the to-be-snapped window ends up being

snapped with the default snap ratio.

For example, when a 1/3-partial snapped window is re-snapped via

overview mode, the window gets 1/2-snapped regardless of the previous

snap ratio. So the overview mode should check the snappability with the

default snap ratio instead of the current ratio in that case.



This CL also renames the overloaded `CanSnapWindow` method as

`CanKeepCurrentSnapRatio` to make the condition clear.

entry.title: Use network::ResourceRequest instead of WebURLRequest in ResourceFetcher
entry.content:
blink::WebURLRequest is used for the argument of

URLLoaderThrottleProvider::CreateThrottles() method after [1]. But we

are planing to call this method from the background thread where we

don't use blink::WebURLRequest [2]. Also we are planing to deprecate

blink::WebURLRequest, and planing to use network::ResourceRequest

instead [3].



So this CL changes the argument type of CreateThrottles() from

blink::WebURLRequest to network::ResourceRequest.

A network::ResourceRequest is created in ResourceLoader::Start(). So we

pass the reference of the structure through ResourceFetcher::

CreateURLLoader().



In frames:

ResourceLoader::Start()

-> ResourceFetcher::CreateURLLoader()

-> LoaderFactoryForFrame::CreateURLLoader()

|-> URLLoaderThrottleProvider::CreateThrottles()

|-> ServiceWorkerNetworkProviderForFrame::

| GetSubresourceLoaderFactory()

|-> URLLoaderFactory::CreateURLLoader()



In workers:

ResourceLoader::Start()

-> ResourceFetcher::CreateURLLoader()

-> LoaderFactoryForWorker::CreateURLLoader()

|-> WebWorkerFetchContext::CreateThrottles()

| -> WebServiceWorkerFetchContextImpl::CreateThrottles() or

| DedicatedOrSharedWorkerFetchContextImpl::CreateThrottles()

| -> URLLoaderThrottleProvider::CreateThrottles()

|-> URLLoaderFactory::CreateURLLoader()



mojom::blink::RequestContextType in blink::WebURLRequest is checked in

the code path. But this type member is not in network::ResourceRequest.

network::ResourceRequest has a network::mojom::RequestDestination

member. And some of these checks of mojom::blink::RequestContextType can

be safely converted to network::mojom::RequestDestination without any

behavior change. But the check in ResourceFetcher::CreateURLLoader()

needs the mojom::blink::RequestContextType. Also we need to pass

`service_worker_race_network_request_token` to

LoaderFactoryForWorker::CreateURLLoader(), and

`is_from_origin_dirty_style_sheet` flag to

ServiceWorkerNetworkProviderForFrame::GetSubresourceLoaderFactory().

So this CL adds these three arguments to CreateURLLoader() methods.



[1]: https://crrev.com/c/994152

[2]: https://crrev.com/c/5113665

[3]: https://groups.google.com/a/chromium.org/forum/#!topic/platform-architecture-dev/ntSzerId4gw
